'''Vadims Vasi<U+013C>evskis''' (born January 5, 1982 in [[Riga]]) is a [[Latvia]]n [[javelin throw]]er, a silver medalist of [[2004 Summer Olympics]]. Vasi<U+013C>evskis achieved his best result of 90.73m on July 22, 2007 in [[Tallinn]], [[Estonia]], becoming the tenth longest javelin thrower of all times.

In his early career he finished eighth at the [[2000 World Junior Championships in Athletics|2000 World Junior Championships]] and competed at the [[2002 European Championships in Athletics|2002 European Championships]] without reaching the final.

Vasi<U+013C>evskis was the [[Latvia at the 2004 Summer Olympics|Latvian]] flag bearer at the [[2004 Summer Olympics]]. He was the biggest surprise among Latvia's medal winners in 2004 Olympics. Latvia had three competitors in javelin throw: Vasi<U+013C>evskis, [[<U+0112>riks Rags]] and [[Voldem<U+0101>rs L<U+016B>sis]], with Vasi<U+013C>evskis being the youngest and the least known of the three. In Olympics, Vasi<U+013C>evskis was the best of the three, throwing for 84.95 metres, two and a half meters further than his previous personal best and good enough to win a silver medal. 

After the Olympic silver he finished eighth at the [[2004 IAAF World Athletics Final|2004 World Athletics Final]]. After an unsuccessful [[2005 World Championships in Athletics - Men's Javelin|2005 World Championships]] where he did not reach the final round, he got fourth places  fourth at the [[2006 European Athletics Championships|2006 European Championships]], the [[2006 IAAF World Athletics Final|2006 World Athletics Final]] and the [[2007 World Championships in Athletics - Men's javelin throw|2007 World Championships]]. He won the gold medal at the [[Athletics at the 2007 Summer Universiade|2007 Summer Universiade]], and finished ninth at the [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics - Men's javelin throw|2008 Olympic Games]]. He was the Latvian flag bearer at the 2008 Summer Olympics as well.

==Season's bests by year==
* 600g
** 55.56 m (1997)
** 69.40 m (1998)
* 700g
** 60.65 m (1998)
** 74.06 m (1999)
* 800g
** 63.82 m (1999)
** 73.07 m (2000)
** 73.25 m (2001)
** 81.92 m (2002)
** 76.81 m (2003)
** 84.95 m (2004)
** 81.30 m (2005)
** 90.43 m (2006)
** 90.73 m (2007)
** 85.78 m (2008)

